227. pedibus deae: ᾖε. under Minerva's statue. This must have been set up by the Trojans when the Palladium was stolen. Virgil's idea was perhaps suggested by statues of Minerva, which sometimes have a serpent at the base. teguntur: hide themselves ; middle voice.

Note that Virgil does not describe the actual death of Laocoon and his sons. This reticence is in accord With the spirit of the best classic art.

(This Laocoon scene has been very carefully composed. Allitera- tive effects are especially common. Thus besides the striking lines 199, 209, 213 (see notes) we have ivi-provida peccora 200, sorte sacerdos 201, Tenedo tranquilla 203, pelasso pariter 205, sanquineae superant 207, suffecti sanquine 210, lambebant linquis 211, miseros morsu 215, capite cervicibus 219. Note, too, the expressive assonance in horresco referens 204, clamores horrendos 222, and incertam exous- εῖτ cervice securim 224.

The spondaic rhythm lends a solemn tone to the act of sacrifice (202) and has an onomatopoetic effect in 223, while the dactylic line at the close (227) accords with the idea of easy motion.)
